A compound membranous cytoplasmic organelle of eukaryotic cells consisting of flattened ribosome-free vesicles arranged in a more or less regular stack. The Golgi apparatus differs from the endoplasmic reticulum in often having slightly thicker membranes appearing in sections as a characteristic shallow semicircle so that the convex side (cis or entry face) abuts the endoplasmic reticulum secretory vesicles emerging from the concave side (trans or exit face).
